description.text:
This is a VERY beta design. I was inspired by a video on YouTube of a guy making a battery out of an aluminum can, copper wire, and salt water. http://www.youtube.com/watch?v=yA6Jde77UNc As a kid I had made similar batteries using zinc, copper, and salt water. For this you will need:
  • Copper wire
  • A small sheet of zinc - although you could modify the design and make it work with a galvanized nail (aka zinc coated nail)
  • Bits of wire
  • Salt water
  • Some acetone or ABS glue if you want to seal it
  • A MakerBot that can print water tight objects
    • My 'bot is out of commission for a few days, so I won't get a chance to try this out for a little while. If you do try, please let me know how the design works for you.

• Print both parts
  • Bend a long piece of copper wire into a small hook at one end and then a thick coil, leaving a long unbent piece at the end
  • Put the hook through the loop in "A" (This is represented by the blue squiggles)
  • Punch a small hole into the sheet of zinc and either bend a piece of wire around it or solder a piece of wire to it (This is represented by the green stuff, with the wire being the purple stuff)
  • Bend a thin sheet of zinc into a cylinder and place it into the groove in "B"
  • Put the long unbent end of the copper wire through the hole in the lid
  • Put the wire from the zinc sheet through the hole in the lid
  • Fill with salt water mixture
  • Close the lid on top (and seal with acetone or ABS glue if you like)
    • Edit:
  • A drop of acetone or ABS glue should create a watertight seal around the holes for the anode leads.

title: Poleshoes - Insulated Terminals For 12V Lead Acid Batteries

description.text:
I like to use old 12V car batteries for all type of projects which require more portable power than what is reasonable available with small rechargeable NiMH or Lithium-Ion batteries. One problem I had, is how to cleanly connect the cable to the battery. The usual battery clamps are do not provide insulation of the battery poles, rather they even increase the exposed metal surface which is prone to produce (potentially very hazardous!) short circuits. So the aim of this little project is to generate insulated battery terminals that can be used to connect cables to standard 12V lead acid batteries. The terminals are designed for applications in which 12V car type batteries are (ab-)used to power low current applications up to about 20A charging resp. load currents. An example of such a project is using an old car battery to store energy collected by a solar panel.
These pole shoes provide a good and stable electrical connection as well as they insulate to open poles to prevent accidental short circuits.
To connect the end of 1.5mm2 insulated stranded wire to the terminal, strip the insulation at about 20mm and insert the end of the wire into the vertical hole until the insulated part is even with the horizontal hole. Then insert the bare copper part through the hole into the inside of the pole shoe and split it into the strands, so as to optimally contact the battery pole on a large area. For even better hold of the cable, I make a small knot into the very end of the insulated part of the wire, after it passed the first hole. Push the pole shoes firmly onto the conical battery poles and fasten them by means of two M3x12 screws and the corresponding nuts.
I recommend printing the positive pole (+) using red filament and the negative pole (-) using green or black filament.
Update 2014-08-05: I uploaded updated versions of the files, which take explicitly into account that the cone of the minus pole is slightly smaller than the con of the plus pole. There are now also a "+" or a "-" signs engraved on the top of the pole shoes.
Update 2014-08-06: I just uploaded an improved version of these pole shoes which directly incorporates a fuse holder, avoiding the risk of a cable melt-down due to an accidentally shorting. I strongly recommend using either the fused version on at least one pole or else integrating some external fuse right into the power cable.

I printed the pole shoes on my RepRap Prusa i3 using an 0.4mm nozzle with extrusion width of 0.56mm and layer height 0.25mm.
Given that for clamping the pole shoes some flexing is desired, ABS seems to be the material of choice here.

Simple place two 1/4 in magnets in the two furthest holes and place a dial indicator in the main hole.On the Rigidbot make sure that the nozzle is the correct height above the bed using a paper shim (only need to set one corner).  Now place the jig on the 8mm rods on the X-axis in that corner. Adjust the bezel to read zero or tear on a digital dial indicator. Move the Bed to check the adjacent corner and then move the jig to check the other two corners. Once initial calibrations have been done it should be a very short process to verify the bed is still level.

This is a project started to make a metal detector. I'm using arduino and electronic components from this page: http://hackaday.com/2013/07/25/build-your-own-metal-detector/
I have designed the 3D printable parts. I'm hoping this will gain contributors and ideas so that this project can rival the expensive commercial metal detectors. As of this writing there is a long way to go. The project is hosted at https://solar1.net/drupal/metal_detector

Print the base search coil and the pivot. The male part of the pivot should epoxy into the inside diameter of a 3/4 inch PVC pipe. I bent the handle end of the PVC with a torch for better comfort.
The electronics are quite simple right now. Is uses a simple oscillator outlined here: http://dzlsevilgeniuslair.blogspot.dk/2013/07/diy-arduino-based-metal-detector.html
The circuit itself is very unstable. I had a hard time keeping the frequency stable enough away from metal to get a reading on anything. I wasn't sure if noise from the Arduino was causing the frequency to shift. If I did manage to get it stable is does pick up metal signals easily.
The next version should use a BFO (Beat Freq. Oscillator) or a VLF to become more accurate.

description.text:
The standard K8200 extruder filament entry guide will wear down pretty fast when printing particulate-loaded, abrasive filaments like brick, ceramic, or glow-in-the-dark. This improved filament entry guide should last at least 3x longer (note the photo showing a worn-out standard guide on the right and the improved guide on the left. grab the big ears with a pair of pliers and out she pops!

I designed the guide in OpenSCAD (pull down the file), measuring my worn-out extruder guide as a template.

description.text: This appliance sold for around $100 a decade ago, but I picked one up at Goodwill for $12. I forgot to test it before leaving the store, and when I got home it just clicked like it had a stripped gear. It was quite a pain to take apart, but the last gear before the big one that drives the opener was indeed missing two teeth. Designing this replacement only took 20 minutes, and after 90 or so minutes of printing I had the mechanism working.

Printed with raft and support, 3 shells and 100% infill because i really don't want to take this apart again. The old gear looked like nylon, but I printed in ABS. The only finishing required beyond peeling away support material was opening up the center bore with a drill.
You only need an assortment of Phillips-head screwdrivers to take the thing apart. I would recommend keeping all parts upside-down so the screws stay in their holes and making a note of the orientation of the spring in the top that holds pressure on the release mechanism.

After processing the photos to create sharp, clear and bright images, I exported them as 16-bit tiffs, masked them and created png masks. I finally imported the tiffs and png masks into Photoscan Pro and created the model of the gravestone. I exported it as a ply and image map for texture.

description.text:
Crank arm which fits onto LEGO (R) Technic cross-shaped axles. When assembled correctly, the handle spins freely on the M3 screw without binding. SCAD file provided so you can make a different crank arm length, handle etc.
It took me 8 iterations to get the "+" shaped socket to be a snug friction-fit on the axle without being too stiff, but the file has been tuned for my printer (UM2, PLA at 20 mm/s, 223 C) and may need adjustment for a perfect fit with any other printer.

Print out one each crank arm and round handle. The assembly uses one M3 screw (25mm long), two M3 nuts and two M3 washers. One nut is captive in the crank arm on the handle side, the other nut goes on the opposite side of the crank arm so the nut is clamped to the arm and the handle can spin freely, but held in place by the head of the M3 screw.

"I will literally explode" - Ryan North Update Feb 11: We blew it up! Full story on Wired: http://www.wired.com/design/2013/02/ryan-north-kickstarted-head-pop/ Ryan's promise to explode after reaching the $500,000 mark on his book's Kickstarter inspired me to reach out to him, and offer the services of Site 3 coLaboratory in order to help him fulfill his goal. The first step was to make a 3D scan of Ryan using ReconstructMe and a Microsoft Kinect: http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/breadpig/to-be-or-not-to-be-that-is-the-adventure/posts/384256 Next, I cleaned up the 3D scan and have now uploaded a mini-bust version that everyone can print out at home. See a video of one being printed: http://youtu.be/zcCjJxf-oew Finally, we used a large-scale 3D print of just the head portion (plus embedded energy drink bottle) for explodening. More info:
To Be Or Not To Be: http://www.kickstarter.com/projects/breadpig/to-be-or-not-to-be-that-is-the-adventure
Site 3 coLaboratory: http://site3.ca
Derek Q.: http://www.techknight.com
ReconstructMe: http://www.reconstructme.net

The head version (ryan_north-HEAD.zip) contains the STL file parts, as well as the Netfabb project I used to split it into sections that fit on my MakerBot Cupcake. There are also optional, further split versions of the middle3 and middle4 parts that save a lot of time by reducing the amount of support material during a print. The chamber inside fits a NOS energy drink bottle.
The mini-bust (ryan_north-BUST.stl) is fully repaired/processed and scaled way down in size to 65mm tall. (It fits on a MakerBot Cupcake.) Don't feel shy about scaling it up! From the video you can see that printing it out really small lost a fair bit of detail on the shop's RepRap.
The raw version (ryan_north-RAW.stl) is the unaltered 3D scan as produced by ReconstructMe. You might want to start with that version if you'd like to do some fancy remixing. (Although the mini-bust version is just fine for stuff like turning Ryan into a Pez head!)

Use a 6-32 screw from each side to join the LCD brackets to the front panel brackets.
The screw holes are deliberately undersized and need to be cleaned up with about a 9/64" drill.
Printing with the nut cavity facing the build plate worked best for me.
